{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"1e751534-ae3f-4043-936e-d44a95063c23","content":"Here's the equivalent command for Microsoft.Testing.Platform:\n\n```bash\ndotnet test -- \\\n  --filter \"Category=Integration\" \\\n  --report-trx \\\n  --coverage --coverage-output-format cobertura \\\n  --crashdump \\\n  --hangdump --hangdump-timeout 5m\n```\n\n**Key changes:**\n| VSTest | Microsoft.Testing.Platform |\n|---|---|\n| `--filter` (before `--`) | `--filter` (after `--`) |\n| `--logger trx` | `--report-trx` |\n| `--collect \"Code Coverage;Format=cobertura\"` | `--coverage --coverage-output-format cobertura` |\n| `--blame-crash` | `--crashdump` |\n| `--blame-hang` | `--hangdump` |\n| `--blame-hang-timeout 5m` | `--hangdump-timeout 5m` |\n\n**Required NuGet packages** (add to your test project):\n```xml\n<PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport\" />\n<PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CodeCoverage\" />\n<PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CrashDump\" />\n<PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.HangDump\" />\n```\n\nAll platform-specific args go **after** the `--` separator so `dotnet test` forwards them to the Microsoft.Testing.Platform host.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"7c9c617e-4e9f-4ec0-bf82-cc3811e26cd5","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating a `dotnet test` command from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MSTest runner) on .NET 8. This is a knowledge question about .NET testing tooling migration, not a codebase task. Let me provide the answer based on my knowledge.\n\nKey differences when moving to Microsoft.Testing.Platform:\n\n1. **Filter**: `--filter` becomes `--filter` still works but the syntax might differ. Actually, with Microsoft.Testing.Platform, when running via `dotnet test`, the `--filter` flag still works. But when running the test executable directly, it's `--filter`.\n\n\n2. **Logger**: `--logger trx` becomes `--report-trx` for built-in TRX report generation.\n3. **Code Coverage**: `--collect \"Code Coverage;Format=cobertura\"` changes to `--coverage --coverage-output-format cobertura` or integrates with the Microsoft.CodeCoverage package.\n4. **Blame**: `--blame-crash`, `--blame-hang`, and `--blame-hang-timeout 5m` map to `--crashdump`, `--hangdump`, and `--hangdump-timeout 5m` respectively.\n\nLet me verify the exact flag mappings more carefully.\n\nWith Microsoft.Testing.Platform, the command-line interface differs depending on whether you're running through `dotnet test` or directly executing the test binary. For .NET 8, I need to check if `dotnet test` supports the new platform natively or if I should use `dotnet run` or the executable directly. The filter syntax and other options will change based on this approach.\n\nNow I'm mapping out how the common MSTest options translate to Microsoft.Testing.Platform equivalents. The filter syntax shifts to tree node filtering, and features like TRX reporting, code coverage, and crash dumps require adding specific NuGet packages and using their corresponding command-line flags instead of the traditional `dotnet test` options.\n\nWhen using `dotnet test` with Microsoft.Testing.Platform on .NET 8, platform-specific arguments go after `--`, so I'd pass something like the filter flag from `dotnet test` itself, then use `--` to separate the platform-specific options like reporting, coverage, and dump collection.\n\nLet me clarify the exact approach here—with `dotnet test` integration for Microsoft.Testing.Platform on .NET 8, the traditional `dotnet test` flags still work for basic filtering, but the newer platform-specific features need to be passed after the `--` separator.\n\nI should also note the NuGet packages required to enable each feature: the trx reporting extension, the code coverage extension, and the crash/hang dump extensions all need to be referenced in the project for those command-line flags to work.","outputTokens":